TODO: Persona-based chat endpoint with topic guardrailing
Add a new direct endpoint (e.g. POST /chat/store-clerk or a generic POST /chat/:persona)
that bypasses the agent loop (direct generate() call, like the endpoints above) and:
  - Uses a crafted system prompt to simulate a specific persona (e.g. a food-store clerk).
  - Enforces topic boundaries: politely refuses off-topic questions
    ("I'm sorry, I'm just a clerk here — I can only help with food-related questions!").
  - Option A (simple): single model + single call — system prompt enforces both role and guardrail.
  - Option B (robust): two-step guard — phi4-mini (AGENT_MODEL_ROUTER_MODEL) classifies
    on-topic/off-topic first; main model (llama3.1:8b-instruct-q8_0, AGENT_MODEL_FAST)
    responds in character only when on-topic.
  - Request body: { message: string, storeContext?: string, conversationHistory?: {role, content}[] }
    storeContext can inject a product catalog, daily specials, store hours, etc.
  - Reuse existing rate-limiting and timeout infrastructure from this file.
Good fit for small businesses wanting a domain-specific chatbot at zero ongoing cost (local Ollama).

TODO: Optional cloud LLM provider layer (secondary priority — local-first remains the focus)
Add an opt-in abstraction that allows routing specific profiles to a cloud API instead of Ollama.
  - Introduce an ILlmProvider interface in packages/llm/types.ts with generate() and
    generateWithMetadata() methods, so Ollama becomes one provider among many.
  - Add an OpenAI-compatible provider (packages/llm/openai-compat-provider.ts) that works with:
    • GitHub Models (https://models.inference.ai.azure.com) — free tier with GitHub Pro
    • OpenAI (api.openai.com)
    • OpenRouter (openrouter.ai) — single key, many models
    • Anthropic (with minor adaptation)
  - Add a "cloud" ModelProfile to the model router; when CLOUD_LLM_API_KEY is unset,
    the profile silently falls back to the local default (zero disruption).
  - New env vars: CLOUD_LLM_PROVIDER, CLOUD_LLM_BASE_URL, CLOUD_LLM_API_KEY, CLOUD_LLM_MODEL.
  - Router integration: either force "cloud" per-request via profile param, or let the
    rules/model router escalate to cloud for tasks that exceed local model capability.
  - Keep it 100 % optional — no API key means the system behaves exactly as before.

DEFERRED: Context overflow pause (Phase 2C)
When context exceeds AGENT_BUDGET_MAX_CONTEXT_CHARS, pause the loop and return a structured
"context_overflow" status with a condensed summary, allowing the client to decide whether to
continue with reduced context or rephrase the task. Requires a /run API contract update
(status field, resumeContext support). Deferred to avoid breaking the current simple
request/response contract.

DEFERRED: MCP bridge integration (Phase 4B)
Add MCP (Model Context Protocol) server support so Manna can consume tools from the growing
MCP ecosystem (GitHub, Slack, databases, etc.) without building each integration from scratch.
See AnythingLLM's server/utils/MCP/ for a reference implementation.

TODO (PR5): Auth gateway wrapper
Add a thin authentication gateway service that sits in front of Manna and handles all auth
concerns without touching the core agent server.
  - Create apps/gateway/ (or a single-file gateway service) that:
    • Validates API keys from the Authorization: Bearer <key> header against env vars.
    • Proxies all authenticated requests to MANNA_URL (default http://manna:3001).
    • Adds rate-limiting, CORS, and request logging at the gateway level.
  - Register as a separate docker-compose service (gateway service on port 8080).
  - New env vars: GATEWAY_API_KEYS (comma-separated), MANNA_URL, GATEWAY_PORT.
  - Manna itself stays completely untouched (no auth logic in the agent server).
  - Pattern: Client → [Gateway :8080] → [Manna :3001]
  - Reference: Express http-proxy-middleware + express-rate-limit.
  - Priority: LOW — local-only Manna does not need auth. Implement when deploying publicly.
  - Reference discussion: see prior conversation context (auth middleware Q&A).
